Our country is based on capitalism and most of those who are wealthy worked hard to get where they are - and continue to work hard every day.  They deserve every dime they've earned and it's not right to take it away from them and give it to those who are less fortunate.  In many cases, those who are at the bottom 20% have not shown any initiative to better themselves.  Rather, they wait for handouts - as have been provided over the course of the past number of decades, and it's become a lifestyle for them.  In some cases they're angry at the lack of opportunity - but ample opportunity exists for those who reach for it.  I'm all for helping the poor, but all against equalizing wealth by stripping from the wealthy who have earned their wealth - and giving it to the less fortunate who, in many cases, have not tried to help themselves.  If we follow such a policy, where will it end?  Those at the bottom 20% who just wait for handouts will only want more and more over time.  Such a philosophy is not sustainable over the long-term.

There are long term effects of such policies that need to be taken into account. It isn't just "take from the rich and give to the poor" and everybody lives happily ever after. I think many people think that way unfortunately. If we enact a policy that raises taxes on the top 20%, there are repercussions for that policy down the road that need to be factored in to that decision. Jobs will likely be lost. Is it worth more people earning zero income to help the rest earn a little bit more? I'm not saying it isn't, but it's something that needs to be considered that most people don't think about. Many times the jobs that the rich create are not even direct employees of their businesses. Let's say they "squander" their fortune on vacation homes, yachts and expensive dinners. Well, who builds those homes and yachts? Who works in the kitchens of those restaurants and waits on the guests and busses the tables and food runs? So to answer your question more directly, the only time I voted for a policy that raised taxes on the top 20% is if the bottom 20% received twice as much (percentage wise). One also needs to remember that a certain percent from the top 20% is worth a lot more in real dollars than the same percent from the bottom 20%, so I was unsure if that was taken into account in your questioning. For example if the question was decreasing the rich's wealth by 10% and increasing the poor's wealth by 10%, does that mean all the money from the rich is going to the poor? Because that would be a lot more than a 10% increase.
